{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4bc52df0-de03-4c5a-8c50-6d85a77f03d9","content":"No worries — here's how to configure it. Create `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for local MCP servers).\n- **`command` / `args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and start your server. Adjust the `--project` path if needed.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, replace `command` with the path to the executable and drop `args`.\n\nAfter saving, restart VS Code or run **\"MCP: List Servers\"** from the command palette to verify it connects.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3de7e87a-f82f-46fc-adca-03a801262d4b","outputTokens":237},"id":"574d5469-24d3-4a3b-b759-983c454eb01c","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:47:26.628Z","parentId":"6f58c32f-4fe1-4fe4-853b-f7179b93d105"}
